{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"801b24ee-978a-4565-afea-5b0b5a2fb932","content":"\n\n`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the **page** not to add safe-area padding, but the **view** itself may still be laid out within safe boundaries. You likely need two more things:\n\n### 1. `IgnoreSafeArea` on the Image (critical for iOS)\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n```\n\n### 2. Edge-to-edge mode on Android\nIn your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    // Draw behind system bars\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n\n    // Make bars transparent\n    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Hide Shell chrome (if using Shell)\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n```\n\n**TL;DR** — `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` stops the *page* padding, but `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the *view* is what actually lets it extend behind system bars on iOS. On Android you must also opt into edge-to-edge via `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ef828b9-e756-4def-8704-9c920e32b150","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI edge-to-edge display on .NET 10. This is a common issue — setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't enough. In .NET MAUI (.NET 10), you need to opt into edge-to-edge rendering, which involves a few steps.\n\nLet me think about what's needed:\n\n1. In .NET 10 MAUI, Android 15+ enforces edge-to-edge by default, but for the app to actually draw behind system bars, you need to handle it properly.\n\n2. The key thing the user is likely missing is that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on ContentPage controls whether the page respects safe areas, but the actual edge-to-edge behavior requires additional configuration.\n\n\n3. The real solution involves using `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views or the page itself, and on Android specifically, you'll need to configure the status bar and navigation bar transparency through platform-specific settings. On iOS, the safe area insets still apply unless you explicitly handle them, while Android's system bars require separate configuration to achieve true edge-to-edge rendering. have been changes around edge-to-edge support. The key things:\n\n1. **Android**: Starting with .NET 9/.NET 10, Android enforces edge-to-edge. You need to make the status bar and navigation bar transparent, and handle insets.\n\n2. **iOS**: You need to ignore safe areas.\n\nThe user set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on ContentPage, but they likely also need `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the Image or its parent layout — that's the iOS-specific mechanism. For Android edge-to-edge in .NET 10, they may need to configure the Window or use platform-specific APIs to make the system bars transparent. If they're using Shell, they might also need to hide the navigation and tab bars. The key distinction is that `SafeAreaEdges` controls padding on the page itself, while `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on individual views actually extends them into unsafe areas—and on Android, edge-to-edge rendering is typically default for Android 15+ targets, though you may need to handle transparent status and navigation bars explicitly.\n\nFor the Image specifically, I need to apply `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` to either the Image or its parent container, and on Android I can use `Window.MakeEdgeToEdge()` or configure lifecycle events to set the system windows behavior and make those bars transparent.","outputTokens":1655},"id":"d0ddf76f-0ed6-4691-971f-99fcd14589a8","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:50:05.512Z","parentId":"b61dc404-e832-4c82-a806-e9c19a25